{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17528298","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17528298"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:40:49+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:40:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14286"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14286","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14286"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.6,0.18,0.11,0.08,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6981"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101284"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6981","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6981"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14286"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"83714"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"37"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"675"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"1804"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"2545"},{"type":"tags","id":"2546"},{"type":"tags","id":"4097"},{"type":"tags","id":"4640"},{"type":"tags","id":"4705"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"4983"},{"type":"tags","id":"4991"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11622"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11643"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"16470"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33191"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33833"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36957"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43515"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44416"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45032"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101284","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/101284"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 20-year-old Aboriginal woman from a remote community in the Northern Territory presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-week history of a non-itchy rash. She also reports fatigue, mild fever, and generalised aches. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. She works as a bus driver. She reports unprotected sexual intercourse with more than one partner in the past six months.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well. Her pulse rate is 82/min, blood pressure 125/75 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.8\u00b0C. There is a copper-coloured maculopapular rash on her trunk and extremities, including her palms and soles (Image). There are several painless, enlarged lymph nodes in her neck and groin. Condylomata lata is noted around the anus. Blood and urine tests are being arranged.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"A positive result in which one of the following investigations is most likely to influence management of this patient\u0027s underlying condition?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Beta human chorionic gonadotropin","Chlamydia urinary nucleic acid amplification test","Gonorrhoea vaginal swab","Hepatitis B serology","Hepatitis C serology"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic features of secondary syphilis, including a copper-coloured maculopapular rash involving palms and soles, generalised lymphadenopathy, condylomata lata, and constitutional symptoms. Secondary syphilis is the systemic stage of syphilis infection (caused by \u003Cem\u003ETreponema pallidum\u003C/em\u003E) occurring at the same time as or up to six months after resolution of the primary chancre. Patients with secondary syphilis are highly infectious.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn a woman of child-bearing age, \u003Cstrong\u003Ebeta human chorionic gonadotropin\u003C/strong\u003E testing is vital to exclude pregnancy, as syphilis can have harmful effects on both mother and baby. If pregnancy is confirmed, the management approach changes significantly, requiring urgent referral to infectious diseases and high-risk obstetric services. The standard treatment for syphilis (benzathine penicillin G) remains the same, but dosing schedules and follow-up protocols differ for pregnant women. Prevention of mother-to-child transmission of syphilis is essential as congenital syphilis can cause severe complications including miscarriage, stillbirth, neonatal death, preterm delivery, and intrauterine growth restriction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChlamydia urinary nucleic acid amplification test\u003C/strong\u003E is important as part of comprehensive STI screening, but a positive result would not significantly alter the management of syphilis. Chlamydia would be treated separately with azithromycin or doxycycline, which would not impact the penicillin treatment for syphilis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGonorrhoea vaginal swab\u003C/strong\u003E testing is also part of routine STI screening, but like chlamydia, a positive result would require separate treatment that would not change the approach to managing syphilis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHepatitis B serology\u003C/strong\u003E is important for overall health assessment and to determine vaccination status, but would not immediately impact the management of syphilis. Co-infection might influence long-term follow-up but would not change the initial treatment approach.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHepatitis C serology\u003C/strong\u003E similarly would not alter the immediate management of syphilis. While important for the patient\u0027s overall health, hepatitis C treatment would be addressed separately from syphilis treatment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt\u0027s worth noting that in remote Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander communities in Northern Australia, there are higher notification rates of sexually transmitted infections. Syphilis is a nationally notifiable condition, and all cases must be reported to the appropriate public health authorities.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["All women of childbearing age with suspected syphilis require pregnancy testing due to risk of congenital transmission.","Adverse clinical outcomes include miscarriage, stillbirth and neonatal death, pre-term delivery, intra-uterine growth restriction and congenital syphilis.","Syphilis in pregnancy requires urgent specialist referral and specific treatment considerations."],"references":["Remote Primary Health Care Manuals. Tropical Health Orientation Manual. Alice Springs, NT: Centre for Remote Health; 2020"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"83714"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14286"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21070"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21070","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21070"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/FO4ZcUITQAyEtH98rY1ppoeAJ0WOMc.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/FO4ZcUITQAyEtH98rY1ppoeAJ0WOMc.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":513,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"83714","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/83714"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-01T09:49:17+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-01T09:50:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6981"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101284"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attri